{"title_page": "Alexis L\u00f3pez (rower)", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican rower}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = Alexis L\u00f3pez\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        =\n| birth_name     =  \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = Mexican\n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1997|5|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mexicali, Baja California]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         =  \n| weight         =  \n| website        = \n| country        = Mexico\n| sport          = [[Rowing]]\n| event          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           =   \n| team           =  \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{MEX}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]]|[[Rowing at the 2019 Pan American Games|Lightweight double sculls]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]]|[[Rowing at the 2019 Pan American Games|Lightweight coxless four]]}}\n}}\n'''Alexis Bladimir L\u00f3pez Garc\u00eda''' (born 1 May 1997 in [[Mexicali, Baja California|Mexicali]]) is a Mexican rower.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mexicoenbarranquilla2018.com/player/alexis-bladimir-lopez-garcia/ |title=Alexis Bladimir L\u00f3pez Garc\u00eda |language=es |website=Barranquilla 2018 |access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lavozdelafrontera.com.mx/deportes/tricampeonbajacaliforniamexicalideportesremomexicali-3105170.html |title=Alexis L\u00f3pez, Tricampe\u00f3n del mundo |language=es |website=[[La Voz de la Frontera]] |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe won the bronze medal at the [[2016 World Rowing U23 Championships]].\nHe won the final B at the [[2017 World Rowing Championships \u2013 Men's lightweight single sculls|2017 World Championships \u2013 lightweight single sculls]].\nHe won the gold medal at [[Rowing at the 2019 Pan American Games|2019 Pan American Games]] in the lightweight double sculls, and also a silver medal at lightweight coxless four.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/46198/lopez-garcia-alexis World Rowing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:L\u00f3pez, Alexis}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican male rowers]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in rowing]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican rower}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = Alexis L\u00f3pez\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        =\n| birth_name     =  \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = Mexican\n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1997|5|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mexicali, Baja California]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         =  \n| weight         =  \n| website        = \n| country        = Mexico\n| sport          = [[Rowing]]\n| event          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           =   \n| team           =  \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{MEX}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]]|[[Rowing at the 2019 Pan American Games|Lightweight double sculls]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]]|[[Rowing at the 2019 Pan American Games|Lightweight coxless four]]}}\n}}\n'''Alexis Bladimir L\u00f3pez Garc\u00eda''' (born 1 May 1997 in [[Mexicali, Baja California|Mexicali]]) is a Mexican rower.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mexicoenbarranquilla2018.com/player/alexis-bladimir-lopez-garcia/ |title=Alexis Bladimir L\u00f3pez Garc\u00eda |language=es |website=Barranquilla 2018 |access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lavozdelafrontera.com.mx/deportes/tricampeonbajacaliforniamexicalideportesremomexicali-3105170.html |title=Alexis L\u00f3pez, Tricampe\u00f3n del mundo |language=es |website=[[La Voz de la Frontera]] |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe won the bronze medal at the [[2016 World Rowing U23 Championships]].\nHe won the final B at the [[2017 World Rowing Championships \u2013 Men's lightweight single sculls|2017 World Championships \u2013 lightweight single sculls]].\nHe won the gold medal at [[Rowing at the 2019 Pan American Games|2019 Pan American Games]] in the lightweight double sculls, and also a silver medal at lightweight coxless four.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/46198/lopez-garcia-alexis World Rowing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:L\u00f3pez, Alexis}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican male rowers]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in rowing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexis_L%C3%B3pez_(rower)"}
{"title_page": "Oliver Mtukudzi", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dr Oliver \"Tuku\" Mtukudzi\n| image            = Tuku.JPG\n| background       = solo_singer\n| caption          = Oliver Mtukudzi and the Black Spirits\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1952|09|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Highfield, Harare|Highfield]], [[Harare|Salisbury]], [[Southern Rhodesia]]<br/><small>(modern-day [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]])</small>\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|1|23|1952|9|22}}\n| death_place      = Harare, Zimbabwe\n| origin           = [[Zimbabwean|Zimbabwe]]\n| genre            = Afro Jazz\n| instrument       = Guitars\n| years_active     = 1977-2019\n| associated_acts  = [[Thomas Mapfumo]], [[Simon Chimbetu]], [[System Tazvida]], [[Winky D]], [[Hugh Masekela]], [[Ringo Madlingozi]], [[Jah Prayzah]], [[Josh Meck]]\n| website          = [http://www.tukutribute.com tukutribute.com]\n}}\n\n'''Oliver \"Tuku\" Mtukudzi''' (22 September 1952 \u2013 23 January 2019) was a [[Zimbabwean]] musician, businessman, philanthropist, [[Human rights activists|human rights activist]] and [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador]] for [[Southern Africa|Southern Africa Region]]. Tuku was considered to have been Zimbabwe's most renowned and internationally recognised cultural icon of all time.\n\n==Biography==\nMtukudzi grew up in [[Highfield, Harare|Highfield]], a poor neighborhood in [[Harare|Salisbury]] (modern-day Harare) in [[Southern Rhodesia]], as the eldest of seven siblings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pindula.co.zw/Oliver_Mtukudzi|title=Oliver Mtukudzi - Pindula|website=pindula.co.zw|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> While both his parents sang in a choir, they were initially not supportive of his continued interest in music, consequently breaking his first homemade guitar.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mafundikwa |first1=Ish |title=The Great Tuku: When It Comes to Music, No One Beats Oliver Mtukudzi in Zimbabwe |journal=New African |date=January 2012 |issue=513 |url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-277602642/the-great-tuku-when-it-comes-to-music-no-one-beats }}</ref> \n\nHe began performing in 1977 when he joined the Wagon Wheels, a band that also featured [[Thomas Mapfumo]] and fellow legendary guitarist [[James Chimombe]]. They were given the rare opportunity by [[Paul Tangi Mhova Mkondo]], an [[African nationalist]] and music promoter, who provided money and resources to the group. With the support of Mutanga, the prayers and blessings of Amai Mutanga, he allowed them to perform at Mutanga Restaurant & Night Club (Pungwe) which, at the time, was the first and only African licensed (obtained by Mkondo) [[night club]] available for blacks under Rhodesia's policy of segregation. Their single ''Dzandimomotera'' went gold and Tuku's first album followed, which was also a major success. Mtukudzi is also a contributor to Mahube, Southern Africa's \"supergroup\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embargo.ca/zim/artists/bios/omtuku/index.htm |title=Oliver Mtukudzi and the Black Spirits, Zimbabwe Music Guide. |access-date=3 September 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070828031842/http://www.embargo.ca/zim/artists/bios/omtuku/index.htm |archive-date=28 August 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWith his husky voice, Mtukudzi has become the most recognised voice to emerge from Zimbabwe and onto the international scene and he has earned a devoted following across Africa and beyond. A member of Zimbabwe's [[Shona people|KoreKore group]], with Nzou Samanyanga as his totem, he sings in the nation's dominant [[Shona language]] along with [[Northern Ndebele language|Ndebele]] and English. He also incorporates elements of different musical traditions, giving his music a distinctive style, known to fans as ''Tuku Music''.  Mtukudzi has had a number of tours around the world. He has been on several tours in the UK, US and Canada to perform for large audiences. In 2017 Mtukudzi entertained guests at the wedding of Zimbabwean businessman [[Wicknell Chivayo]].<ref>{{ cite news|url=https://www.herald.co.zw/tuku-serenades-chivayos-marriage-ceremony-guests/|title=Tuku serenades Chivayo's marriage ceremony guests|accessdate=10 January 2017 |work=The Herald}}</ref>\n\n2003 - Oliver Mtukudzi founded Pakare Paye as an Arts Centre providing a performance platform for developing and fostering young talent in many practical artistic endeavours particularly music, dance, drama, poetry and storytelling. Pakare Paye developed the following artists who are well established in their own rights; Munyaradzi Mataruse (seasoned), upcoming and artists of the moment who also performed on the funeral of Dr Oliver Mtukudzi; Innocent \"Answer\" Kufakunesu and Ashford \"Mbeu\" Nyahora. Ashford is well established and went on to perform with Tuku's family in Cape Town South Africa at the Jazz Festival where Tuku used to be a regular. The Centre benefited from support from different organisations that included the Culture Fund in partnership with the Embassy of Sweden, Nyaradzo Group and many international organisations. One of the famous products of Pakare Paye includes Mtukudzi's own son Sam, who unfortunately passed on in a car accident in 2010. Sam was a composed musician who could play any instrument and could sing vocals as well. All these prominent students of Tuku perform Afrofusion music that combines jazz and traditional African music and has Tuku touch infused in them. The Centre is also frequented by schools that attend workshops on arts where students get an opportunity to learn that there are various aspects of the music industry they can learn. Some of the schools that visits the Centre regularly include Marlborough High, Mabelreign Girls High, Harare Girls High, Chiedza Primary, Tafara High, Mabvuku High and St Eric\u2019s High, among others. Through Pakare Paye, young Zimbabweans have an opportunity to learn benefits and pitfalls of the music industry as they have the opportunity to interact with veterans in the industry. The Centre provides venues that can be used by musicians and communities for different events.\n \nMtukudzi is the father of five children and has two grandchildren. Two of his children are also musicians. His son [[Sam Mtukudzi]], a successful musician in his own right, died in a car accident in March 2010 and in 2013, he released an album titled \"Sarawoga\", in tribute to his son.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/23/africa/oliver-mtukudzi-zimbabwe-died/index.html|title=Zimbabwean music legend Oliver Mtukudzi has died|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newzimbabwe.com/showbiz-2026-Sam+Mtukudzi+dies+in+car+crash/showbiz.aspx |title=Sam Mtukudzi dies in car crash |publisher=Newzimbabwe.com |date=15 March 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317173643/http://www.newzimbabwe.com/showbiz-2026-Sam+Mtukudzi+dies+in+car+crash/showbiz.aspx |archive-date=17 March 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/local/2010/03/15/oliver-mtukudzi-s-son-dies-in-car-crash |title=Oliver Mtukudzi's son dies in car crash |publisher=Times LIVE |date=15 March 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Social commentary==\nPrior to the independence of [[Zimbabwe]], Mtukudzi's music depicted the struggles under [[Southern Rhodesia | Rhodesian]] white minority rule.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-47021184|title=Mtukudzi buried in his home village|date=2019-01-27|access-date=2019-01-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> In subsequent years following [[Rhodesian Bush War | Zimbabwean independence]], his music has advocated for tolerance and peace and has frequently portrayed the struggles of women and children.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oliver Mtukudzi and his 'talking guitar' was our gift from Zimbabwe to the world |url=https://qz.com/africa/1534462/oliver-mtukudzi-was-our-gift-from-zimbabwe-to-the-world/ |website=Quartz Africa }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn 23 January 2019, Mtukudzi died at the age of 66 at Avenues Clinic in [[Harare]], Zimbabwe after a long battle with [[diabetes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/music-legend-oliver-mtukudzis-guitar-strums-silenced-in-diabetes-battle/ |title=Music legend Oliver Mtukudzi's guitar strums silenced in diabetes battle |website=Nairobi News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==''Discography''==\n\n# 1978 ''Ndipeiwo Zano'' (re-released 2000)\n# 1979 ''Chokwadi Chichabuda''\n# 1979 ''Muroi Ndiani?''\n# 1980 ''Africa'' (re-released 2000)\n# 1981 ''Shanje''\n# 1981 ''Pfambi''\n# 1982 ''Maungira''\n# 1982 ''Please Ndapota''\n# 1983 ''Nzara''\n# 1983 ''Oliver's Greatest Hits''\n# 1984 ''Hwema Handirase''\n# 1985 ''Mhaka''\n# 1986 ''Gona''\n# 1986 ''Zvauya Sei?''\n# 1987 ''Wawona''\n# 1988 ''Nyanga Nyanga ''\n# 1988 ''Strange, Isn't It?'\n# 1988 ''Sugar Pie''\n# 1989 ''Grandpa Story''\n# 1990 ''Chikonzi''\n# 1990 ''Pss Pss Hallo!''\n# 1990 ''Shoko''\n# 1991 ''Mutorwa''\n# 1992 ''Rombe''\n# 1992 ''Rumbidzai Jehova''\n# 1992 ''Neria Soundtrack'\n# 1993 ''Son of Africa''\n# 1994 ''Ziwere MuKobenhavn''\n# 1995 ''Was My Child''\n# 1996 ''Svovi yangu''\n# 1995 ''The Other Side: Live in Switzerland''\n# 1995 ''Ivai Navo''\n# 1997 ''Ndega Zvangu'' (re-released 2001)\n# 1997 ''Chinhamwe''\n# 1998 ''Dzangu Dziye''\n# 1999 ''Tuku Music''\n# 2000 ''Paivepo''\n# 2001 ''Neria''\n# 2001 ''Bvuma'' (Accept)\n# 2002 ''Shanda'' soundtrack\n# 2002 ''Vhunze Moto''\n# 2003 ''Shanda '' ([[Alula Records]])\n# 2003 ''Tsivo'' (Revenge)\n# 2004 ''Greatest Hits Tuku Years''\n# 2004 ''Mtukudzi Collection 1991\u20131997''\n# 2004 ''Mtukudzi Collection 1984\u20131991''\n# 2005 ''Nhava'' (Tolerance)\n# 2006 ''Wonai''\n# 2007 ''Tsimba Itsoka''\n# 2008 ''Dairai'' (Believe)\n# 2010 ''Rudaviro''\n# 2010 ''Kutsi Kwemoyo'' (compilation)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tuku debuts double album on UK tour|url=http://newzimsituation.com/594505f/tuku-debuts-double-album-on-uk-tour.htm|date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2010|publisher=New Zimbabwe}}</ref>\n# 2011 ''Rudaviro''\n# 2011 ''Abi'angu'' (Duets of My Time)\n# 2012 ''Sarawoga'' \u2014 Sarawoga laments the losses that the legend has had to endure in his life, not least the loss of life. Thus he has been left 'alone' in a sense, hence the title Sarawoga (left alone).\n# 2014 ''Mukombe Wemvura''\n# 2016 ''God Bless You - The Gospel Collection''\n# 2016 ''Eheka! Nhai Yahwe''\n# 2018 ''hany\u2019a''  (Concern)\n\n===Contributing artist===\n# 1996 ''[[The Rough Guide to the Music of Zimbabwe]]'' ([[World Music Network]])\n# 1999 ''[[Unwired: Acoustic Music from Around the World]]'' (World Music Network)\n# 2000 ''[[Unwired: Africa]]'' (World Music Network)\n\n==''Filmography''==\n* ''[[Jit (film)|Jit]]'' (dir. [[Michael Raeburn]], 1990)\n*''[[Neria]]'' (dir. Goodwin Mawuru, written by [[Tsitsi Dangarembga]], 1993). Mtukudzi starred in the movie and made the soundtrack.\n* ''[[Shanda (Movie)|Shanda]]'' (dir. John and Louise Riber, 2002, rev. 2004)<ref>[http://www.dandemutande.org/Catalog/?cat=Films&subcat=Music&artist=MtukudziOliver#Shanda Review of Shanda movie at Dandamutande]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* ''Sarawoga'', 2009, was written by Elias C. Machemedze, directed by Watson Chidzomba and produced by Oliver Mtukudzi, who also did the soundtrack for the film.\n*2012 Nzou NeMhuru Mudanga DVD, the live recording of a show, a theatrical performance which Tuku had with his son just weeks before his death.\n\n==Awards==\n*1985\u20131988: One of The Best Selling Artists in Zimbabwe.\n* [[KORA Award]] for Best Arrangement in 2002, for Ndakuwara.\n*2002: SAMA Finalist (Best Traditional/African Adult Contemporary DVD) Live at the Cape Town Jazz Festival.\n* National Arts Merit Awards (NAMA) in 2002 and 2004 for Best Group / Male vocalist\n* [[KORA Award]] for Best African male artist and Lifetime Achievement Award in August 2003.\n* [[Channel O Music Video Awards|Reel Award]] Winner for Best African Language in 2003.\n* An honorary degree from the [[University of Zimbabwe]] in December 2003<ref>{{cite news|title=Mtukudzi, Ringo expected for UK concerts|publisher= New Zimbabwe.com|date= 11 October 2006 |url=http://www.newzimbabwe.com/pages/tuku9.11817.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927025436/http://www.newzimbabwe.com/pages/tuku9.11817.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 }}</ref>\n* NAMA Award 2003: Best Group/Artist.\n* NAMA Award 2004: Best Group/Artist.\n* NAMA Award 2005: National Arts Personality of the Year.\n* NAMA Award 2006: Outstanding Album (NHAVA).\n*2006: ZIMA (Best Music Ringing Tone Handiro Dambudziko).\n*2006: ZIMA (Music Ambassador).\n* NAMA Award 2007: Best Musician/Group.\n*2007:Cultural Ambassador \u2013 Zimbabwe Tourism Association.\n* NAMA Award 2008: (Outstanding Musician).\n* Honorary MSc (Fine Arts) Degree awarded by the Women's University in Africa in 2009.\n* M-Net Best Soundtrack Award in 1992, for Neria<ref>[http://www.sheer.co.za/oliver.html Oliver Mtukudzi:Biography, Sheer Sound]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2010: MTN SAMA Awards recognised his son's achievements in music.\n* 2010: University of Zimbabwe (UZ) and The International Council of Africana Womanism (ICAW) Award: recognition of his luminary role in uplifting African women through his artistic work \u2013 music and a diversity of art forms \u2013 offered as community development at his arts academy at Pakare Paye in Norton.\n* 2011: Titled Zimbabwe's first UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador for Eastern and Southern Africa.\n* 2011: Honoured by the Government of Italy with the prestigious Cavaliere of the Order of Merit Award in recognition of his work as an international musician. (The award is what the Knighthood is to England).\n* 2014 Honorary Doctorate (PHD) International Institute of Philanthropy.\n* 2014 Honorary Doctorate from Great Zimbabwe University (GZU). Doctor of Philosophy in Ethnomusicology & Choreography (Honoris Causa).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mtukudzi, Oliver}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean musicians]]\n[[Category:Heads Up International artists]]\n[[Category:People from Harare]]\n[[Category:20th-century singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century singers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dr Oliver \"Tuku\" Mtukudzi\n| image            = Tuku.JPG\n| background       = solo_singer\n| caption          = Oliver Mtukudzi and the Black Spirits\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1952|09|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Highfield, Harare|Highfield]], [[Harare|Salisbury]], [[Southern Rhodesia]]<br/><small>(modern-day [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]])</small>\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|1|23|1952|9|22}}\n| death_place      = Harare, Zimbabwe\n| origin           = [[Zimbabwean|Zimbabwe]]\n| genre            = Afro Jazz\n| instrument       = Guitars\n| years_active     = 1977-2019\n| associated_acts  = [[Thomas Mapfumo]], [[Simon Chimbetu]], [[System Tazvida]], [[Winky D]], [[Hugh Masekela]], [[Ringo Madlingozi]], [[Jah Prayzah]], [[Josh Meck]]\n| website          = [http://www.tukutribute.com tukutribute.com]\n}}\n\n'''Oliver \"Tuku\" Mtukudzi''' (22 September 1952 \u2013 23 January 2019) was a [[Zimbabwean]] musician, businessman, philanthropist, [[Human rights activists|human rights activist]] and [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador]] for [[Southern Africa|Southern Africa Region]]. Tuku was considered to have been Zimbabwe's most renowned and internationally recognised cultural icon of all time.\n\n==Biography==\nMtukudzi grew up in [[Highfield, Harare|Highfield]], a poor neighborhood in [[Harare|Salisbury]] (modern-day Harare) in [[Southern Rhodesia]], as the eldest of seven siblings<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pindula.co.zw/Oliver_Mtukudzi|title=Oliver Mtukudzi - Pindula|website=pindula.co.zw|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>. While both his parents sang in a choir, they were initially not supportive of his continued interest in music, consequently breaking his first homemade guitar.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mafundikwa |first1=Ish |title=The Great Tuku: When It Comes to Music, No One Beats Oliver Mtukudzi in Zimbabwe |journal=New African |date=January 2012 |issue=513 |url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-277602642/the-great-tuku-when-it-comes-to-music-no-one-beats }}</ref> \n\nHe began performing in 1977 when he joined the Wagon Wheels, a band that also featured [[Thomas Mapfumo]] and fellow legendary guitarist [[James Chimombe]]. They were given the rare opportunity by [[Paul Tangi Mhova Mkondo]], an [[African nationalist]] and music promoter, who provided money and resources to the group. With the support of Mutanga, the prayers and blessings of Amai Mutanga, he allowed them to perform at Mutanga Restaurant & Night Club (Pungwe) which, at the time, was the first and only African licensed (obtained by Mkondo) [[night club]] available for blacks under Rhodesia's policy of segregation. Their single ''Dzandimomotera'' went gold and Tuku's first album followed, which was also a major success. Mtukudzi is also a contributor to Mahube, Southern Africa's \"supergroup\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embargo.ca/zim/artists/bios/omtuku/index.htm |title=Oliver Mtukudzi and the Black Spirits, Zimbabwe Music Guide. |access-date=3 September 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070828031842/http://www.embargo.ca/zim/artists/bios/omtuku/index.htm |archive-date=28 August 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWith his husky voice, Mtukudzi has become the most recognised voice to emerge from Zimbabwe and onto the international scene and he has earned a devoted following across Africa and beyond. A member of Zimbabwe's [[Shona people|KoreKore group]], with Nzou Samanyanga as his totem, he sings in the nation's dominant [[Shona language]] along with [[Northern Ndebele language|Ndebele]] and English. He also incorporates elements of different musical traditions, giving his music a distinctive style, known to fans as ''Tuku Music''.  Mtukudzi has had a number of tours around the world. He has been on several tours in the UK, US and Canada to perform for large audiences. In 2017 Mtukudzi entertained guests at the wedding of Zimbabwean businessman [[Wicknell Chivayo]].<ref>{{ cite news|url=https://www.herald.co.zw/tuku-serenades-chivayos-marriage-ceremony-guests/|title=Tuku serenades Chivayo's marriage ceremony guests|accessdate=10 January 2017 |work=The Herald}}</ref>\n\n2003 - Oliver Mtukudzi founded Pakare Paye as an Arts Centre providing a performance platform for developing and fostering young talent in many practical artistic endeavours particularly music, dance, drama, poetry and storytelling. Pakare Paye developed the following artists who are well established in their own rights; Munyaradzi Mataruse (seasoned), upcoming and artists of the moment who also performed on the funeral of Dr Oliver Mtukudzi; Innocent \"Answer\" Kufakunesu and Ashford \"Mbeu\" Nyahora. Ashford is well established and went on to perform with Tuku's family in Cape Town South Africa at the Jazz Festival where Tuku used to be a regular. The Centre benefited from support from different organisations that included the Culture Fund in partnership with the Embassy of Sweden, Nyaradzo Group and many international organisations. One of the famous products of Pakare Paye includes Mtukudzi's own son Sam, who unfortunately passed on in a car accident in 2010. Sam was a composed musician who could play any instrument and could sing vocals as well. All these prominent students of Tuku perform Afrofusion music that combines jazz and traditional African music and has Tuku touch infused in them. The Centre is also frequented by schools that attend workshops on arts where students get an opportunity to learn that there are various aspects of the music industry they can learn. Some of the schools that visits the Centre regularly include Marlborough High, Mabelreign Girls High, Harare Girls High, Chiedza Primary, Tafara High, Mabvuku High and St Eric\u2019s High, among others. Through Pakare Paye, young Zimbabweans have an opportunity to learn benefits and pitfalls of the music industry as they have the opportunity to interact with veterans in the industry. The Centre provides venues that can be used by musicians and communities for different events.\n \nMtukudzi is the father of five children and has two grandchildren. Two of his children are also musicians. His son [[Sam Mtukudzi]], a successful musician in his own right, died in a car accident in March 2010 and in 2013, he released an album titled \"Sarawoga\", in tribute to his son.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/23/africa/oliver-mtukudzi-zimbabwe-died/index.html|title=Zimbabwean music legend Oliver Mtukudzi has died|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newzimbabwe.com/showbiz-2026-Sam+Mtukudzi+dies+in+car+crash/showbiz.aspx |title=Sam Mtukudzi dies in car crash |publisher=Newzimbabwe.com |date=15 March 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317173643/http://www.newzimbabwe.com/showbiz-2026-Sam+Mtukudzi+dies+in+car+crash/showbiz.aspx |archive-date=17 March 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/local/2010/03/15/oliver-mtukudzi-s-son-dies-in-car-crash |title=Oliver Mtukudzi's son dies in car crash |publisher=Times LIVE |date=15 March 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Social commentary==\nPrior to the independence of [[Zimbabwe]], Mtukudzi's music depicted the struggles under [[Southern Rhodesia | Rhodesian]] white minority rule.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-47021184|title=Mtukudzi buried in his home village|date=2019-01-27|access-date=2019-01-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> In subsequent years following [[Rhodesian Bush War | Zimbabwean independence]], his music has advocated for tolerance and peace and has frequently portrayed the struggles of women and children.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oliver Mtukudzi and his 'talking guitar' was our gift from Zimbabwe to the world |url=https://qz.com/africa/1534462/oliver-mtukudzi-was-our-gift-from-zimbabwe-to-the-world/ |website=Quartz Africa }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn 23 January 2019, Mtukudzi died at the age of 66 at Avenues Clinic in [[Harare]], Zimbabwe after a long battle with [[diabetes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/music-legend-oliver-mtukudzis-guitar-strums-silenced-in-diabetes-battle/ |title=Music legend Oliver Mtukudzi's guitar strums silenced in diabetes battle |website=Nairobi News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==''Discography''==\n\n# 1978 ''Ndipeiwo Zano'' (re-released 2000)\n# 1979 ''Chokwadi Chichabuda''\n# 1979 ''Muroi Ndiani?''\n# 1980 ''Africa'' (re-released 2000)\n# 1981 ''Shanje''\n# 1981 ''Pfambi''\n# 1982 ''Maungira''\n# 1982 ''Please Ndapota''\n# 1983 ''Nzara''\n# 1983 ''Oliver's Greatest Hits''\n# 1984 ''Hwema Handirase''\n# 1985 ''Mhaka''\n# 1986 ''Gona''\n# 1986 ''Zvauya Sei?''\n# 1987 ''Wawona''\n# 1988 ''Nyanga Nyanga ''\n# 1988 ''Strange, Isn't It?'\n# 1988 ''Sugar Pie''\n# 1989 ''Grandpa Story''\n# 1990 ''Chikonzi''\n# 1990 ''Pss Pss Hallo!''\n# 1990 ''Shoko''\n# 1991 ''Mutorwa''\n# 1992 ''Rombe''\n# 1992 ''Rumbidzai Jehova''\n# 1992 ''Neria Soundtrack'\n# 1993 ''Son of Africa''\n# 1994 ''Ziwere MuKobenhavn''\n# 1995 ''Was My Child''\n# 1996 ''Svovi yangu''\n# 1995 ''The Other Side: Live in Switzerland''\n# 1995 ''Ivai Navo''\n# 1997 ''Ndega Zvangu'' (re-released 2001)\n# 1997 ''Chinhamwe''\n# 1998 ''Dzangu Dziye''\n# 1999 ''Tuku Music''\n# 2000 ''Paivepo''\n# 2001 ''Neria''\n# 2001 ''Bvuma'' (Accept)\n# 2002 ''Shanda'' soundtrack\n# 2002 ''Vhunze Moto''\n# 2003 ''Shanda '' ([[Alula Records]])\n# 2003 ''Tsivo'' (Revenge)\n# 2004 ''Greatest Hits Tuku Years''\n# 2004 ''Mtukudzi Collection 1991\u20131997''\n# 2004 ''Mtukudzi Collection 1984\u20131991''\n# 2005 ''Nhava'' (Tolerance)\n# 2006 ''Wonai''\n# 2007 ''Tsimba Itsoka''\n# 2008 ''Dairai'' (Believe)\n# 2010 ''Rudaviro''\n# 2010 ''Kutsi Kwemoyo'' (compilation)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tuku debuts double album on UK tour|url=http://newzimsituation.com/594505f/tuku-debuts-double-album-on-uk-tour.htm|date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=2 August 2010|publisher=New Zimbabwe}}</ref>\n# 2011 ''Rudaviro''\n# 2011 ''Abi'angu'' (Duets of My Time)\n# 2012 ''Sarawoga'' \u2014 Sarawoga laments the losses that the legend has had to endure in his life, not least the loss of life. Thus he has been left 'alone' in a sense, hence the title Sarawoga (left alone).\n# 2014 ''Mukombe Wemvura''\n# 2016 ''God Bless You - The Gospel Collection''\n# 2016 ''Eheka! Nhai Yahwe''\n# 2018 ''hany\u2019a''  (Concern)\n\n===Contributing artist===\n# 1996 ''[[The Rough Guide to the Music of Zimbabwe]]'' ([[World Music Network]])\n# 1999 ''[[Unwired: Acoustic Music from Around the World]]'' (World Music Network)\n# 2000 ''[[Unwired: Africa]]'' (World Music Network)\n\n==''Filmography''==\n* ''[[Jit (film)|Jit]]'' (dir. [[Michael Raeburn]], 1990)\n*''[[Neria]]'' (dir. Goodwin Mawuru, written by [[Tsitsi Dangarembga]], 1993). Mtukudzi starred in the movie and made the soundtrack.\n* ''[[Shanda (Movie)|Shanda]]'' (dir. John and Louise Riber, 2002, rev. 2004)<ref>[http://www.dandemutande.org/Catalog/?cat=Films&subcat=Music&artist=MtukudziOliver#Shanda Review of Shanda movie at Dandamutande]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* ''Sarawoga'', 2009, was written by Elias C. Machemedze, directed by Watson Chidzomba and produced by Oliver Mtukudzi, who also did the soundtrack for the film.\n*2012 Nzou NeMhuru Mudanga DVD, the live recording of a show, a theatrical performance which Tuku had with his son just weeks before his death.\n\n==Awards==\n*1985\u20131988: One of The Best Selling Artists in Zimbabwe.\n* [[KORA Award]] for Best Arrangement in 2002, for Ndakuwara.\n*2002: SAMA Finalist (Best Traditional/African Adult Contemporary DVD) Live at the Cape Town Jazz Festival.\n* National Arts Merit Awards (NAMA) in 2002 and 2004 for Best Group / Male vocalist\n* [[KORA Award]] for Best African male artist and Lifetime Achievement Award in August 2003.\n* [[Channel O Music Video Awards|Reel Award]] Winner for Best African Language in 2003.\n* An honorary degree from the [[University of Zimbabwe]] in December 2003<ref>{{cite news|title=Mtukudzi, Ringo expected for UK concerts|publisher= New Zimbabwe.com|date= 11 October 2006 |url=http://www.newzimbabwe.com/pages/tuku9.11817.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927025436/http://www.newzimbabwe.com/pages/tuku9.11817.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 }}</ref>\n* NAMA Award 2003: Best Group/Artist.\n* NAMA Award 2004: Best Group/Artist.\n* NAMA Award 2005: National Arts Personality of the Year.\n* NAMA Award 2006: Outstanding Album (NHAVA).\n*2006: ZIMA (Best Music Ringing Tone Handiro Dambudziko).\n*2006: ZIMA (Music Ambassador).\n* NAMA Award 2007: Best Musician/Group.\n*2007:Cultural Ambassador \u2013 Zimbabwe Tourism Association.\n* NAMA Award 2008: (Outstanding Musician).\n* Honorary MSc (Fine Arts) Degree awarded by the Women's University in Africa in 2009.\n* M-Net Best Soundtrack Award in 1992, for Neria<ref>[http://www.sheer.co.za/oliver.html Oliver Mtukudzi:Biography, Sheer Sound]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2010: MTN SAMA Awards recognised his son's achievements in music.\n* 2010: University of Zimbabwe (UZ) and The International Council of Africana Womanism (ICAW) Award: recognition of his luminary role in uplifting African women through his artistic work \u2013 music and a diversity of art forms \u2013 offered as community development at his arts academy at Pakare Paye in Norton.\n* 2011: Titled Zimbabwe's first UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador for Eastern and Southern Africa.\n* 2011: Honoured by the Government of Italy with the prestigious Cavaliere of the Order of Merit Award in recognition of his work as an international musician. (The award is what the Knighthood is to England).\n* 2014 Honorary Doctorate (PHD) International Institute of Philanthropy.\n* 2014 Honorary Doctorate from Great Zimbabwe University (GZU). Doctor of Philosophy in Ethnomusicology & Choreography (Honoris Causa).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mtukudzi, Oliver}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean musicians]]\n[[Category:Heads Up International artists]]\n[[Category:People from Harare]]\n[[Category:20th-century singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century singers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Mtukudzi"}
{"title_page": "Oligomenorrhea", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Oligomenorrhea \n| synonyms        = Oligomenorrhoea\n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[Gynecology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Oligomenorrhea''' is infrequent (or, in occasional usage, very light) [[menstruation]].<ref name=gale/> More strictly, it is menstrual periods occurring at intervals of greater than 35 days, with only four to nine periods in a year.<ref name=gale>[http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/oligomenorrhea thefreedictionary.com > oligomenorrhea] This dictionary is citing Gale Encyclopedia of Medicine. 2008</ref> Menstrual periods should have been regularly established before the development of infrequent flow.<ref name=gale/> The duration of such events may vary.<ref>{{cite book| vauthors=Berek JS, Adashi EY, Hillard PA |title=Novak's Gynecology | url=https://archive.org/details/novaksgynecology00bere | url-access=registration |edition=12th|publisher=Williams & Wilkins|location=Baltimore|year=1996|ISBN=0-683-00593-6}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nOligomenorrhea can be a result of prolactinomas ([[adenomas]] of the anterior [[pituitary]]). It may be caused by [[thyrotoxicosis]], hormonal changes in [[perimenopause]], [[Prader\u2013Willi syndrome]], and [[Graves disease]].\n\nEndurance exercises such as running or swimming can affect the reproductive physiology of women athletes. Female runners,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Dale E, Gerlach DH, Wilhite AL |title=Menstrual dysfunction in distance runners |journal=Obstet Gynecol |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=47\u201353 |year=1979 |pmid=313033 |doi= 10.1097/00006250-197907000-00013|url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wakat DK, Sweeney KA, Rogol AD |title=Reproductive system function in women cross-country runners |journal=Med Sci Sports Exerc |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=263\u20139 |year=1982 |pmid=7132642 |doi= 10.1249/00005768-198204000-00002|url=}}</ref> swimmers<ref>{{cite journal |author=Frisch RE |title=Delayed menarche and amenorrhea of college athletes in relation to age of onset of training |journal=JAMA |volume=246 |issue=14 |pages=1559\u20131563 |year=1981 |pmid=7277629 |doi= 10.1001/jama.246.14.1559|url= |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Gotz-Welbergen AV |author3=McArthur JW |display-authors=3 |last4=Albright |first4=T |last5=Witschi |first5=J |last6=Bullen |first6=B |last7=Birnholz |first7=J |last8=Reed |first8=RB |last9=Hermann |first9=H}}</ref> and ballet dancers<ref>{{cite journal |author=Warren MP |title=The effects of exercise on pubertal progression and reproductive function in girls |journal=J. Clin. Endocrinol. Metab. |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=1150\u20131157 |year=1980 |pmid=6775000 |doi= 10.1210/jcem-51-5-1150|url=}}</ref> either menstruate infrequently in comparison to non-athletic women of comparable age or exhibit [[amenorrhea]]. A more recent study shows that athletes competing in sports that emphasise thinness or a specific weight exhibit a higher rate of menstrual dysfunction than either athletes competing in sports with less focus on these or control subjects.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Torsiveit, MK |title=Participation in leanness sports but not training volume is associated with menstrual dysfunction: a national survey of 1276 elite athletes and controls |journal=British Journal of Sports Medicine |volume=39 |issue=3 |pages=141\u2013147 |year=2005 |doi= 10.1136/bjsm.2003.011338 |url=|pmc=1725151 |pmid=15728691}}</ref>\n\nBreastfeeding has been linked to irregularity of menstrual cycles due to hormones that delay ovulation.\n\nWomen with [[polycystic ovary syndrome]] (PCOS) are also likely to have oligomenorrhea. PCOS is a condition in which excessive [[androgens]] (male sex hormones) are released by the [[ovaries]]. Women with PCOS show menstrual irregularities that range from oligomenorrhea and amenorrhea, to very heavy, irregular periods. The condition affects about 6% of premenopausal women.\n\nEating disorders can result in oligomenorrhea. Although menstrual disorders are most strongly associated with [[anorexia nervosa]], [[bulimia nervosa]] may also result in oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea. There is some controversy regarding the mechanism for the menstrual dysregulation, since amenorrhea may sometimes precede substantial weight loss in some anorexics.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Amenorrhoea|Amenorrhea]]: a total cessation of the menstrual period\n* [[Menorrhagia]]: unusually heavy periods\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|N|91|5|n|80}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|626.1}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = \n|   eMedicineTopic = \n|   DiseasesDB     = 14843 \n}}\n{{Diseases of the pelvis, genitals and breasts}}\n{{Menstrual cycle}}\n\n[[Category:Menstrual disorders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Oligomenorrhea \n| synonyms        = Oligomenorrhoea\n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[Gynecology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Oligomenorrhea''' is infrequent (or, in occasional usage, very light) [[menstruation]].<ref name=gale/> More strictly, it is menstrual periods occurring at intervals of greater than 35 days, with only four to nine periods in a year.<ref name=gale>[http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/oligomenorrhea thefreedictionary.com > oligomenorrhea] This dictionary is citing Gale Encyclopedia of Medicine. 2008</ref> Menstrual periods should have been regularly established before the development of infrequent flow.<ref name=gale/> The duration of such events may vary.<ref>{{cite book| vauthors=Berek JS, Adashi EY, Hillard PA |title=Novak's Gynecology | url=https://archive.org/details/novaksgynecology00bere | url-access=registration |edition=12th|publisher=Williams & Wilkins|location=Baltimore|year=1996|ISBN=0-683-00593-6}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nOligomenorrhea can be a result of prolactinomas ([[adenomas]] of the anterior [[pituitary]]). It may be caused by [[thyrotoxicosis]], hormonal changes in [[perimenopause]], [[Prader\u2013Willi syndrome]], and [[Graves disease]].\n\nEndurance exercises such as running or swimming can affect the reproductive physiology of women athletes. Female runners,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Dale E, Gerlach DH, Wilhite AL |title=Menstrual dysfunction in distance runners |journal=Obstet Gynecol |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=47\u201353 |year=1979 |pmid=313033 |doi= 10.1097/00006250-197907000-00013|url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wakat DK, Sweeney KA, Rogol AD |title=Reproductive system function in women cross-country runners |journal=Med Sci Sports Exerc |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=263\u20139 |year=1982 |pmid=7132642 |doi= 10.1249/00005768-198204000-00002|url=}}</ref> swimmers<ref>{{cite journal |author=Frisch RE |title=Delayed menarche and amenorrhea of college athletes in relation to age of onset of training |journal=JAMA |volume=246 |issue=14 |pages=1559\u20131563 |year=1981 |pmid=7277629 |doi= 10.1001/jama.246.14.1559|url= |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Gotz-Welbergen AV |author3=McArthur JW |display-authors=3 |last4=Albright |first4=T |last5=Witschi |first5=J |last6=Bullen |first6=B |last7=Birnholz |first7=J |last8=Reed |first8=RB |last9=Hermann |first9=H}}</ref> and ballet dancers<ref>{{cite journal |author=Warren MP |title=The effects of exercise on pubertal progression and reproductive function in girls |journal=J. Clin. Endocrinol. Metab. |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=1150\u20131157 |year=1980 |pmid=6775000 |doi= 10.1210/jcem-51-5-1150|url=}}</ref> either menstruate infrequently in comparison to non-athletic women of comparable age or exhibit [[amenorrhea]]. A more recent study shows that athletes competing in sports that emphasise thinness or a specific weight exhibit a higher rate of menstrual dysfunction than either athletes competing in sports with less focus on these or control subjects<ref>{{cite journal |author=Torsiveit, MK |title=Participation in leanness sports but not training volume is associated with menstrual dysfunction: a national survey of 1276 elite athletes and controls |journal=British Journal of Sports Medicine |volume=39 |issue=3 |pages=141\u2013147 |year=2005 |doi= 10.1136/bjsm.2003.011338 |url=|pmc=1725151 |pmid=15728691}}</ref>.\n\nBreastfeeding has been linked to irregularity of menstrual cycles due to hormones that delay ovulation.\n\nWomen with [[polycystic ovary syndrome]] (PCOS) are also likely to have oligomenorrhea. PCOS is a condition in which excessive [[androgens]] (male sex hormones) are released by the [[ovaries]]. Women with PCOS show menstrual irregularities that range from oligomenorrhea and amenorrhea, to very heavy, irregular periods. The condition affects about 6% of premenopausal women.\n\nEating disorders can result in oligomenorrhea. Although menstrual disorders are most strongly associated with [[anorexia nervosa]], [[bulimia nervosa]] may also result in oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea. There is some controversy regarding the mechanism for the menstrual dysregulation, since amenorrhea may sometimes precede substantial weight loss in some anorexics.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Amenorrhoea|Amenorrhea]]: a total cessation of the menstrual period\n* [[Menorrhagia]]: unusually heavy periods\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|N|91|5|n|80}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|626.1}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = \n|   eMedicineTopic = \n|   DiseasesDB     = 14843 \n}}\n{{Diseases of the pelvis, genitals and breasts}}\n{{Menstrual cycle}}\n\n[[Category:Menstrual disorders]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligomenorrhea"}
{"title_page": "Alexis Arias (rower)", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Alexis Arias\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Cuban\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1969|10|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Villa Clara Province|Villa Clara]], Cuba\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Alexis Arias''' (born 18 October 1969) is a Cuban [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight double sculls|men's lightweight double sculls]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ar/alexis-arias-1.html |title=Alexis Arias Olympic Results |accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arias, Alexis}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Villa Clara Province]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in rowing]]\n\n\n{{Cuba-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Alexis Arias\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Cuban\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1969|10|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Villa Clara Province|Villa Clara]], Cuba\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Alexis Arias''' (born 18 October 1969) is a Cuban [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight double sculls|men's lightweight double sculls]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ar/alexis-arias-1.html |title=Alexis Arias Olympic Results |accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arias, Alexis}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Villa Clara Province]]\n{{Cuba-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in rowing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexis_Arias_(rower)"}
{"title_page": "Olga Khokhlova", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olga Picasso\n| image         = Olga Khokhlova.jpg\n| alt           = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Olga Khokhlova in ''[[Afternoon of a Faun (Nijinsky)|Afternoon of a Faun]]'', circa 1916\n| birth_name    = Olga Stepanovna Khokhlova\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1891|06|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Nizhyn]], [[Chernigov Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1955|02|11|1891|06|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Cannes, France]]\n| nationality   = Russian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Ballet dancer]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Pablo Picasso]]|1918}}\n| children           = Paulo Picasso\n}}\n\n'''Olga Picasso''', (born '''Olga Stepanovna Khokhlova'''. {{lang-ru|\u041e\u0301\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u0445\u043b\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0430}}, {{lang-uk| \u041e\u0301\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043d\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u0445\u043b\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0430}}, June 17, 1891 &ndash; February 11, 1955) was a [[Russian ballet|Russian ballet dancer]] of [[Nobility|noble descent]]. She was also the first wife of [[Pablo Picasso]], one of his early artistic muses and the mother of his son, Paulo. [[File:Olga Khokhlova in Picasso's Montrouge studio, spring 1918.jpg|thumb|250px|Olga Khokhlova in Picasso's Montrouge studio, spring 1918]]\n[[File:Pablo Picasso, 1917-18, Portrait d'Olga dans un fauteuil (Olga in an Armchair), oil on canvas, 130 x 88.8 cm, Mus\u00e9e Picasso, Paris, France.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Pablo Picasso]], spring 1918, ''Portrait d'Olga dans un fauteuil (Olga in an Armchair)'', oil on canvas, 130 x 88.8 cm, [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]], Paris, France]]\n\n== Biography ==\nOlga Khokhlova was born in the town of [[Nezhin]], [[Chernigov Governorate]], ([[Ukraine]], then located in the [[Russian Empire]]). Her mother Lydia Zinchenko was a Ukrainian of descent. Her father was a Russian officer. The Khokhlovs family had three sons and two daughters. Olga wanted to be a ballerina from the time she visited France and saw Madame Shroessont perform. She became a member of the [[Ballets Russes]] of [[Sergei Diaghilev]].\n\nOn May 18, 1917, Olga danced in ''[[Parade (ballet)|Parade]]'' \u2013 a ballet by [[Sergei Diaghilev]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Jean Cocteau]] \u2013 on its opening night at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Ch\u00e2telet]]. Pablo Picasso had designed the costumes and set for the ballet. After meeting Picasso, Olga left the group, which toured South America, and stayed in [[Barcelona]] with him. He introduced her to his family. At first his mother was alarmed by the idea that her son should marry a foreigner, so he gave her a painting of Olga as a Spanish girl (''Olga Khokhlova in Mantilla''). Later Olga returned with Picasso to [[Paris]], where they began to live together on the [[Rue La Bo\u00e9tie]].\n\n=== Marriage to Picasso ===\nOlga married Picasso on July 12, 1918, at the [[Alexander Nevsky Cathedral, Paris|Russian Orthodox Cathedral]] at the Rue Daru. Jean Cocteau and [[Max Jacob]] were witnesses to the marriage. She was one of Picasso's first artistic muses.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/12132545/Picassos-muses-artists-own-collection-starring-six-women-he-loved-on-sale-for-the-first-time.html Picasso muses, ''The Telegraph'']</ref>\n\nIn July 1919, Pablo and Olga went to [[London]] for the performance of ''[[El Sombrero de Tres Picos|Le Tricorne]]'', for which Picasso had designed costumes and sets, according to Diaghilev's wishes. The ballet was also performed at the [[Alhambra]], in Spain, and was a great success at the [[Op\u00e9ra National de Paris|Paris Opera]] in 1919.\n\nOn February 4, 1921, Olga gave birth to a boy named Paulo (Paul). From then on, Olga and Picasso's relationship deteriorated. In 1927, Picasso began an affair with a seventeen-year-old French woman, [[Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Walter]]. In 1935, Olga learned of the affair from a friend, who also informed her that Walter was pregnant. Immediately, Olga took Paulo, moved to the [[South of France]], and filed for divorce. Picasso refused to divide his property evenly with her, as required by French law, so Olga stayed legally married to him until her death from cancer in [[Cannes]], France, in 1955.\n\n== Descendants ==\nPaulo, who died on June 5, 1975, was married to [[Emilienne Lotte]] and divorced in 1953.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blanc |first1=Jean-Daniel |title=Family tree of \"Paul\" Joseph RUIZ PICASSO |url=https://gw.geneanet.org/elsa2002?lang=en&pz=emma+cecile+rose&nz=valdeyron&p=paul+joseph&n=ruiz+picasso |website=Geneanet |accessdate=10 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> They had two children: Pablito (born on May 5, 1949 \u2013 committed suicide on July 2, 1973) and Marina (born on November 14, 1950). Paulo, later in life, married [[Christiane Pauplin]]. The couples' only child, [[Bernard Ruiz-Picasso]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blanc |first1=Jean-Daniel |title=Family tree of Bernard RUIZ PICASSO |url=https://gw.geneanet.org/elsa2002?lang=en&pz=emma+cecile+rose&nz=valdeyron&p=bernard&n=ruiz+picasso |website=Geneanet |accessdate=10 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>, co-founded the Picasso Museum in Malaga along with his mother.\n\nIn 1990, Marina Picasso founded an orphanage in [[Thu Duc District|Thu Duc]], [[Vietnam]] (a former military base). Named \"The Village of Youth\", it was funded by Marina\u2019s inheritance from her grandfather, Pablo Picasso. Marina\u2019s foundation has also organized the digging of wells in inland Vietnam, sends regular shipments of milk to orphanages and hospitals and grants farming subsidies and scholarships.\n\n== Bibliography==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Richardson\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = John Richardson (art historian)\n  | title = A Life of Picasso: The Triumphant Years, 1917-1932\n  | publisher = [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]]\n  | year = 2007\n  | isbn = 978-0307266651\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/lifeofpicasso00rich\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Picasso\n  | first = Marina\n  | author2 = Louis Valentin\n  | title = Picasso, My Grandfather\n  | publisher = [[Riverhead Books]]\n  | year = 2001\n  | isbn = 978-1573221917\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/picassomygrandfa00pica\n  }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Olga Ruiz Picasso nee Khokhlova}}\n* [http://www.peoples.ru/love/hohlova-picasso/ Biography of Olga Khokhlova] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.picasso-pablo.ru/library/picasso-i-hohlova.html Picasso and Khokhlova] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.pablo-ruiz-picasso.ru/olga.php Retratos de Olga Khokhlova by Picasso] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.pablo-ruiz-picasso.ru/photogallery.php Pictures of Picasso and Khokhlova] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://picassolive.ru/blog/tag/olga-xoxlova-foto/ Biography and pictures of Olga Khokhlova] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{Pablo Picasso}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khoklova, Olga Stepanovna}}\n[[Category:Imperial Russian artists' models]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian ballerinas]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nizhyn]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Cimeti\u00e8re du Grand Jas]]\n[[Category:Muses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olga Picasso\n| image         = Olga Khokhlova.jpg\n| alt           = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Olga Khokhlova in ''[[Afternoon of a Faun (Nijinsky)|Afternoon of a Faun]]'', circa 1916\n| birth_name    = Olga Stepanovna Khokhlova\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1891|06|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Nizhyn]], [[Chernigov Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1955|02|11|1891|06|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Cannes, France]]\n| nationality   = Russian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Ballet dancer]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Pablo Picasso]]|1918}}\n| children           = Paulo Picasso\n}}\n\n'''Olga Picasso''', (born '''Olga Stepanovna Khokhlova'''. {{lang-ru|\u041e\u0301\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u0445\u043b\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0430}}, {{lang-uk| \u041e\u0301\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043d\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u0445\u043b\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0430}}, June 17, 1891 &ndash; February 11, 1955) was a [[Russian ballet|Russian ballet dancer]] of [[Nobility|noble descent]]. She was also the first wife of [[Pablo Picasso]], one of his early artistic muses and the mother of his son, Paulo. [[File:Olga Khokhlova in Picasso's Montrouge studio, spring 1918.jpg|thumb|250px|Olga Khokhlova in Picasso's Montrouge studio, spring 1918]]\n[[File:Pablo Picasso, 1917-18, Portrait d'Olga dans un fauteuil (Olga in an Armchair), oil on canvas, 130 x 88.8 cm, Mus\u00e9e Picasso, Paris, France.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Pablo Picasso]], spring 1918, ''Portrait d'Olga dans un fauteuil (Olga in an Armchair)'', oil on canvas, 130 x 88.8 cm, [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]], Paris, France]]\n\n== Biography ==\nOlga Khokhlova was born in the town of [[Nezhin]], [[Chernigov Governorate]], ([[Ukraine]], then located in the [[Russian Empire]]). Her mother Lydia Zinchenko was a Ukrainian of descent. Her father was a Russian officer. The Khokhlovs family had three sons and two daughters. Olga wanted to be a ballerina from the time she visited France and saw Madame Shroessont perform. She became a member of the [[Ballets Russes]] of [[Sergei Diaghilev]].\n\nOn May 18, 1917, Olga danced in ''[[Parade (ballet)|Parade]]'' \u2013 a ballet by [[Sergei Diaghilev]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Jean Cocteau]] \u2013 on its opening night at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Ch\u00e2telet]]. Pablo Picasso had designed the costumes and set for the ballet. After meeting Picasso, Olga left the group, which toured South America, and stayed in [[Barcelona]] with him. He introduced her to his family. At first his mother was alarmed by the idea that her son should marry a foreigner, so he gave her a painting of Olga as a Spanish girl (''Olga Khokhlova in Mantilla''). Later Olga returned with Picasso to [[Paris]], where they began to live together on the [[Rue La Bo\u00e9tie]].\n\n=== Marriage to Picasso ===\nOlga married Picasso on July 12, 1918, at the [[Alexander Nevsky Cathedral, Paris|Russian Orthodox Cathedral]] at the Rue Daru. Jean Cocteau and [[Max Jacob]] were witnesses to the marriage. She was one of Picasso's first artistic muses.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/12132545/Picassos-muses-artists-own-collection-starring-six-women-he-loved-on-sale-for-the-first-time.html Picasso muses, ''The Telegraph'']</ref>\n\nIn July 1919, Pablo and Olga went to [[London]] for the performance of ''[[El Sombrero de Tres Picos|Le Tricorne]]'', for which Picasso had designed costumes and sets, according to Diaghilev's wishes. The ballet was also performed at the [[Alhambra]], in Spain, and was a great success at the [[Op\u00e9ra National de Paris|Paris Opera]] in 1919.\n\nOn February 4, 1921, Olga gave birth to a boy named Paulo (Paul). From then on, Olga and Picasso's relationship deteriorated. In 1927, Picasso began an affair with a seventeen-year-old French woman, [[Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Walter]]. In 1935, Olga learned of the affair from a friend, who also informed her that Walter was pregnant. Immediately, Olga took Paulo, moved to the [[South of France]], and filed for divorce. Picasso refused to divide his property evenly with her, as required by French law, so Olga stayed legally married to him until her death from cancer in [[Cannes]], France, in 1955.\n\n== Descendants ==\nPaulo, who died on June 5, 1975, was married to [[Emilienne Lotte]] and divorced in 1953<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blanc |first1=Jean-Daniel |title=Family tree of \"Paul\" Joseph RUIZ PICASSO |url=https://gw.geneanet.org/elsa2002?lang=en&pz=emma+cecile+rose&nz=valdeyron&p=paul+joseph&n=ruiz+picasso |website=Geneanet |accessdate=10 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>. They had two children: Pablito (born on May 5, 1949 \u2013 committed suicide on July 2, 1973) and Marina (born on November 14, 1950). Paulo, later in life, married [[Christiane Pauplin]]. The couples' only child, [[Bernard Ruiz-Picasso]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blanc |first1=Jean-Daniel |title=Family tree of Bernard RUIZ PICASSO |url=https://gw.geneanet.org/elsa2002?lang=en&pz=emma+cecile+rose&nz=valdeyron&p=bernard&n=ruiz+picasso |website=Geneanet |accessdate=10 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>, co-founded the Picasso Museum in Malaga along with his mother.\n\nIn 1990, Marina Picasso founded an orphanage in [[Thu Duc District|Thu Duc]], [[Vietnam]] (a former military base). Named \"The Village of Youth\", it was funded by Marina\u2019s inheritance from her grandfather, Pablo Picasso. Marina\u2019s foundation has also organized the digging of wells in inland Vietnam, sends regular shipments of milk to orphanages and hospitals and grants farming subsidies and scholarships.\n\n== Bibliography==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Richardson\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = John Richardson (art historian)\n  | title = A Life of Picasso: The Triumphant Years, 1917-1932\n  | publisher = [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]]\n  | year = 2007\n  | isbn = 978-0307266651\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/lifeofpicasso00rich\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Picasso\n  | first = Marina\n  | author2 = Louis Valentin\n  | title = Picasso, My Grandfather\n  | publisher = [[Riverhead Books]]\n  | year = 2001\n  | isbn = 978-1573221917\n  | url-access 